{
  "text": "Surprisingly, gp91 phox2/-mice had no evidence of decreased neutrophil elastase because increased numbers of neutrophils compensated for the reduction of neutrophil elastase released per cell. Nor was the neutrophil elastase release in gp91 phox2/-mice the consequence of bacterially produced ROS. Potential explanations for the lack of granule-associated proteaseinduced acute lung injury include evidence that ROS inactivate protease inhibitors such as a 1 -antiprotease [CITATION_1] . In keeping with this, our preliminary data have shown evidence of increased levels of secretory leukoprotease inhibitor, an inhibitor of neutrophil-expressed serine proteases, in gp91 phox2/-mice (see Figure E5 ). Neutrophil elastase can modify the inflammatory response by enhancing IL-8 production and inducing shedding of surface expressed receptors [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] .",
  "correct_citation": {
